{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7fdf3d65-4271-456d-9988-63917d797096","content":"The .NET MAUI Android workload **bundles its own JDK** (Microsoft Build of OpenJDK 17). When you set `JAVA_HOME` to a different distribution like Adoptium Temurin, the build picks up that JDK instead, which causes compatibility issues with the Android build tooling.\n\n**Fix:** Unset `JAVA_HOME` so the build uses the bundled JDK automatically:\n\n```bash\n# Remove or comment out any JAVA_HOME export in your ~/.zshrc or ~/.bash_profile\n# Then for the current session:\nunset JAVA_HOME\n```\n\nThen rebuild:\n\n```bash\ndotnet build -t:Rebuild\n```\n\nIf you need `JAVA_HOME` set for other tools, you can point it to the workload-bundled JDK instead. Find it with:\n\n```bash\ndotnet android info\n```\n\nor look under:\n\n```\n/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/microsoft-17.jdk/Contents/Home\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"af09d976-9106-4ed4-bf06-579fe20c76a5","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is having a .NET MAUI Android build failure related to Java. They have Adoptium Temurin JDK 17.0.12 installed. Let me check if there's a known compatibility issue with .NET MAUI and certain JDK versions/distributions.\n\nThis is a well-known issue: .NET MAUI / Xamarin Android builds require the **Microsoft OpenJDK** distribution specifically, or at minimum a JDK 11 that ships with the Android workload. More precisely, the .NET Android SDK workload installs its own Microsoft OpenJDK and expects that to be used.\n\nActually, let me think more carefully. \n\nThe core problem is that .NET 8 MAUI requires JDK 17, and while they have the right version number, the .NET Android SDK specifically ships with and expects the Microsoft Build of OpenJDK 17. Using a different distribution like Adoptium Temurin can cause compatibility issues because the Android SDK toolchain has dependencies on the specific Microsoft build.\n\nThe fix is typically to either unset `JAVA_HOME` so the .NET Android SDK uses its bundled Microsoft OpenJDK, or explicitly install the Microsoft Build of OpenJDK 17. On macOS, the bundled JDK gets installed with the Android workload, though I'm trying to recall the exact installation path for .NET 8+. The issue is that when `JAVA_HOME` points to Temurin, it overrides the bundled Microsoft OpenJDK 17 that comes with the .NET Android workload, causing version mismatches and build failures. The solution is to unset `JAVA_HOME` entirely so the build system uses its own JDK, or explicitly point it to the Microsoft OpenJDK path instead.","outputTokens":1151,"requestId":"9437:3FC561:13C4210:162E795:6A067081"},"id":"f36fffee-48b0-4e92-9e12-2e978695dc31","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:02:19.113Z","parentId":"94e77981-20d0-4277-b072-b622cb94b94e"}
